[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] In computer science, **locality-sensitive hashing** (**LSH**) is a fuzzy hashing technique that hashes similar input items into the same "buckets" with high probability.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The number of buckets is much smaller than the universe of possible input items.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since similar items end up in the same buckets, this technique can be used for data clustering and nearest neighbor search.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] It differs from conventional hashing techniques in that hash collisions are maximized, not minimized.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively, the technique can be seen as a way to reduce the dimensionality of high-dimensional data; high-dimensional input items can be reduced to low-dimensional versions while preserving relative distances between items.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Hashing-based approximate nearest-neighbor search algorithms generally use one of two main categories of hashing methods: either data-independent methods, such as locality-sensitive hashing (LSH); or data-dependent methods, such as locality-preserving hashing (LPH).
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Locality-preserving hashing was initially devised as a way to facilitate data pipelining in implementations of massively parallel algorithms that use randomized routing and universal hashing to reduce memory contention and network congestion.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] if it satisfies the following condition.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively it is possible to define an LSH family on a universe of items U endowed with a similarity function $\phi \colon U\times U\to [0,1]$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] In this setting, a LSH scheme is a family of hash functions H coupled with a probability distribution D over H such that a function $h\in H$ chosen according to D satisfies $Pr[h(a)=h(b)]=\phi (a,b)$ for each $a,b\in U$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given a $(d_{1},d_{2},p_{1},p_{2})$ -sensitive family ${\mathcal {F}}$ , we can construct new families ${\mathcal {G}}$ by either the AND-construction or OR-construction of ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an AND-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an OR-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] We then say that for a hash function $g\in {\mathcal {G}}$ , $g(x)=g(y)$ if and only if $h_{i}(x)=h_{i}(y)$ for one or more values of i.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] One of the easiest ways to construct an LSH family is by bit sampling.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] This approach works for the Hamming distance over d-dimensional vectors $\{0,1\}^{d}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Here, the family ${\mathcal {F}}$ of hash functions is simply the family of all the projections of points on one of the d coordinates, i.e., ${\mathcal {F}}=\{h\colon \{0,1\}^{d}\to \{0,1\}\mid h(x)=x_{i}{\text{ for some }}i\in \{1,\ldots ,d\}\}$ , where $x_{i}$ is the i th coordinate of x .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] A random function h from ${\mathcal {F}}$ simply selects a random bit from the input point.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, any two vectors $x,y$ with Hamming distance at most R collide under a random h with probability at least $P_{1}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Any $x,y$ with Hamming distance at least $cR$ collide with probability at most $P_{2}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Suppose U is composed of subsets of some ground set of enumerable items S and the similarity function of interest is the Jaccard index J.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] If π is a permutation on the indices of S, for $A\subseteq S$ let $h(A)=\min _{a\in A}\{\pi (a)\}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Each possible choice of π defines a single hash function h mapping input sets to elements of S.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Define the function family H to be the set of all such functions and let D be the uniform distribution.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given two sets $A,B\subseteq S$ the event that $h(A)=h(B)$ corresponds exactly to the event that the minimizer of π over $A\cup B$ lies inside $A\cap B$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] As h was chosen uniformly at random, $Pr[h(A)=h(B)]=J(A,B)\,$ and $(H,D)\,$ define an LSH scheme for the Jaccard index.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because the symmetric group on n elements has size n!, choosing a truly random permutation from the full symmetric group is infeasible for even moderately sized n.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because of this fact, there has been significant work on finding a family of permutations that is "min-wise independent" — a permutation family for which each element of the domain has equal probability of being the minimum under a randomly chosen π.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] It has been established that a min-wise independent family of permutations is at least of size $\operatorname {lcm} \{\,1,2,\ldots ,n\,\}\geq e^{n-o(n)}$ , and that this bound is tight.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because min-wise independent families are too big for practical applications, two variant notions of min-wise independence are introduced: restricted min-wise independent permutations families, and approximate min-wise independent families.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Restricted min-wise independence is the min-wise independence property restricted to certain sets of cardinality at most k.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Approximate min-wise independence differs from the property by at most a fixed ε.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The encoding must be robust against intentional attacks.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The encoding should support an extremely low risk of false positives.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Testing performed in the paper on a range of file types identified the Nilsimsa hash as having a significantly higher false positive rate when compared to other similarity digest schemes such as TLSH, Ssdeep and Sdhash.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] An implementation of TLSH is available as open-source software.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The random projection method of LSH due to Moses Charikar called SimHash (also sometimes called arccos) uses an approximation of the cosine distance between vectors.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The technique was used to approximate the NP-complete max-cut problem.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The basic idea of this technique is to choose a random hyperplane (defined by a normal unit vector r) at the outset and use the hyperplane to hash input vectors.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given an input vector v and a hyperplane defined by r, we let $h(v)=\operatorname {sgn}(v\cdot r)$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, $h(v)=\pm 1$ depending on which side of the hyperplane v lies.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] This way, each possible choice of a random hyperplane r can be interpreted as a hash function $h(v)$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since the ratio between ${\frac {\theta (u,v)}{\pi }}$ and $1-\cos(\theta (u,v))$ is at least 0.439 when $\theta (u,v)\in [0,\pi ]$ , the probability of two vectors being on different sides of the random hyperplane is approximately proportional to the cosine distance between them.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The hash function $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}({\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}):{\mathcal {R}}^{d}\to {\mathcal {N}}$ maps a d-dimensional vector ${\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}$ onto the set of integers.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Each hash function in the family is indexed by a choice of random $\mathbf {a}$ and b where $\mathbf {a}$ is a d-dimensional vector with entries chosen independently from a stable distribution and b is a real number chosen uniformly from the range [0,r].
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] For a fixed $\mathbf {a} ,b$ the hash function $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}$ is given by $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}({\boldsymbol {\upsilon }})=\left\lfloor {\frac {\mathbf {a} \cdot {\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}+b}{r}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Other construction methods for hash functions have been proposed to better fit the data.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] In particular k-means hash functions are better in practice than projection-based hash functions, but without any theoretical guarantee.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Semantic hashing is a technique that attempts to map input items to addresses such that closer inputs have higher semantic similarity.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The hashcodes are found via training of an artificial neural network or graphical model.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] One of the main applications of LSH is to provide a method for efficient approximate nearest neighbor search algorithms.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Consider an LSH family ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The algorithm has two main parameters: the width parameter k and the number of hash tables L.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] In the first step, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is obtained by concatenating k functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ , i.e., $g(p)=[h_{1}(p),\ldots ,h_{k}(p)]$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] In other words, a random hash function g is obtained by concatenating k randomly chosen hash functions from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The algorithm then constructs L hash tables, each corresponding to a different randomly chosen hash function g.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] In the preprocessing step we hash all n d-dimensional points from the data set S into each of the L hash tables.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given that the resulting hash tables have only n non-zero entries, one can reduce the amount of memory used per each hash table to $O(n)$ using standard hash functions.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given a query point q, the algorithm iterates over the L hash functions g.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] For each g considered, it retrieves the data points that are hashed into the same bucket as q.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] The process is stopped as soon as a point within distance cR from q is found.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] To generalize the above algorithm without radius R being fixed, we can take the algorithm and do a sort of binary search over R.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] When t is large, it is possible to reduce the hashing time from $O(n^{\rho })$ .
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] It is also sometimes the case that the factor $1/P_{1}$ can be very large.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] This happens for example with Jaccard similarity data, where even the most similar neighbor often has a quite low Jaccard similarity with the query.
[src:pinecone/locality-sensitive-hashing] In it was shown how to reduce the query time to $O(n^{\rho }/P_{1}^{1-\rho })$ (not including hashing costs) and similarly the space usage.
[src:pinecone/main-readme-md] The Pinecone Python SDK provides a client for the Pinecone vector database.
[src:pinecone/main-readme-md] Use it to create and manage indexes, upsert and query vectors, and run inference operations from Python.
[src:pinecone/main-readme-md] A suite of live-API smoke tests verifies that the retry stack and AIMD adaptive concurrency hold up against real Pinecone rate limits.
[src:pinecone/main-readme-md] These are **not** run in normal CI because they require real credentials, create a live serverless index, and take 1–3 minutes per run.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:pinecone/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Learn how Pinecone’s architecture enables fast, relevant vector search at any scale.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Pinecone runs as a managed service on AWS, GCP, and Azure cloud platforms.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] The API gateway first validates your API key to make sure you have permission to access the project.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Once validated, it routes your request to either the global control plane (for managing projects and indexes) or a regional data plane (for reading and writing data), depending on what you’re trying to do.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] The global control plane manages your organizational resources like projects and indexes.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] It uses a dedicated database to keep track of all these objects.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] The control plane also handles billing, user management, and coordinates operations across different regions.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] , and all your data read and write requests target a specific namespace.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Pinecone separates write and read operations into different paths, with each scaling independently based on demand.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] This separation ensures that your queries never slow down your writes, and your writes never slow down your queries.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] For each namespace in a serverless index, Pinecone organizes records into immutable files called slabs.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] and stored in distributed object storage that provides virtually unlimited scalability and high availability.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] first logs the request details with a unique sequence number (LSN).
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] This ensures all operations happen in the correct order and provides a way to track the state of the index.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] response, guaranteeing that your write is durable and won’t be lost.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] The system then processes your write in the background.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] The index builder stores your write data in an in-memory structure called a memtable.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] This includes your vector data, any metadata you’ve attached, and the sequence number.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] If you’re updating or deleting a record, the system also tracks how to handle the old version during queries.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Periodically, the index builder moves data from the memtable to permanent storage.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] , your data is organized into immutable files called slabs.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] These slabs are optimized for query performance.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Smaller slabs use fast indexing techniques that provide good performance with minimal resource requirements.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] As slabs grow, the system merges them into larger slabs that use more sophisticated methods that provide better performance at scale.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] This adaptive process both optimizes query performance for each slab and amortizes the cost of more expensive indexing through the lifetime of the namespace.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] All read operations check the memtable first, so you can immediately search data that you’ve just written, even before it’s moved to permanent storage.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] The query router then identifies which slabs contain relevant data and routes your query to the appropriate executors.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] It also searches the memtable for any recent data that hasn’t been moved to permanent storage yet.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Each query executor searches through its assigned slabs and returns the most relevant candidates to the query router.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] If your query includes metadata filters, the executors exclude records that don’t match your criteria before finding the best matches.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] Most of the time, the slabs are cached in memory or on local SSD, which provides very fast query performance.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] If a slab isn’t cached (which happens when it’s accessed for the first time or hasn’t been used recently), the executor fetches it from object storage and caches it for future queries.
[src:pinecone/serverless-architecture] The query router then combines results from all executors, removes duplicates, merges them with results from the memtable, and returns the final set of best matches to you.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] A **vector database**, **vector store** or **vector search engine** is a database that stores and retrieves embeddings of data in vector space.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Vector databases typically implement approximate nearest neighbor algorithms so users can search for records semantically similar to a given input, unlike traditional databases which primarily look up records by exact match.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Use-cases for vector databases include similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Vector embeddings are mathematical representations of data in a high-dimensional space.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] In this space, each dimension corresponds to a feature of the data, with the number of dimensions ranging from a few hundred to tens of thousands, depending on the complexity of the data being represented.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Each data item is represented by one vector in this space.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Words, phrases, or entire documents, as well as images, audio, and other types of data, can all be vectorized.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] These feature vectors may be computed from the raw data using machine learning methods such as feature extraction algorithms, word embeddings or deep learning networks.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] The goal is that semantically similar data items receive feature vectors close to each other.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Vector retrieval can be combined with metadata filtering or lexical search to support filtered and hybrid retrieval workflows.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] These techniques may also be combined in vector search systems.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] In recent benchmarks, HNSW-based implementations have been among the best performers.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Conferences such as the International Conference on Similarity Search and Applications (SISAP) and the Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) have hosted competitions on vector search in large databases.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Vector databases are used in a wide range of machine learning applications including similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] An especially common use-case for vector databases is in retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), a method to improve domain-specific responses of large language models.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] The retrieval component of a RAG can be any search system, but is most often implemented as a vector database.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Text documents describing the domain of interest are collected, and for each document or document section, a feature vector (known as an "embedding") is computed, typically using a deep learning network, and stored in a vector database along with a link to the document.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] Given a user prompt, the feature vector of the prompt is computed, and the database is queried to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:pinecone/vector-database] These are then automatically added into the context window of the large language model, and the large language model proceeds to create a response to the prompt given this context.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] In this section we consider a particular vector space model based on the bag-of-words representation.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Documents and queries are represented as vectors.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Each dimension corresponds to a separate term.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] If a term occurs in the document, its value in the vector is non-zero.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Several different ways of computing these values, also known as (term) weights, have been developed.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] One of the best known schemes is tf-idf weighting (see the example below).
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] The definition of *term* depends on the application.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Typically terms are single words, keywords, or longer phrases.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] If words are chosen to be the terms, the dimensionality of the vector is the number of words in the vocabulary (the number of distinct words occurring in the corpus).
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Vector operations can be used to compare documents with queries.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Candidate documents from the corpus can be retrieved and ranked using a variety of methods.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Where $\mathbf {d_{2}} \cdot \mathbf {q}$ is the intersection (i.e. the dot product) of the document (d2 in the figure to the right) and the query (q in the figure) vectors, $\left\|\mathbf {d_{2}} \right\|$ is the norm of vector d2, and $\left\|\mathbf {q} \right\|$ is the norm of vector q.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] As all vectors under consideration by this model are element-wise nonnegative, a cosine value of zero means that the query and document vector are orthogonal and have no match (i.e. the query term does not exist in the document being considered).
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] See cosine similarity for further information.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] In the classic vector space model proposed by Salton, Wong and Yang, the term-specific weights in the document vectors are products of local and global parameters.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] The model is known as term frequency–inverse document frequency (tf–idf) model.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Most of these advantages are a consequence of the difference in the density of the document collection representation between Boolean and term frequency-inverse document frequency approaches.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] When using Boolean weights, any document lies in a vertex in a n-dimensional hypercube.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Therefore, the possible document representations are $2^{n}$ and the maximum Euclidean distance between pairs is ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] As documents are added to the document collection, the region defined by the hypercube's vertices become more populated and hence denser.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Unlike Boolean, when a document is added using term frequency-inverse document frequency weights, the inverse document frequencies of the terms in the new document decrease while that of the remaining terms increase.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] In average, as documents are added, the region where documents lie expands regulating the density of the entire collection representation.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] This behavior models the original motivation of Salton and his colleagues that a document collection represented in a low density region could yield better retrieval results.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Many of these difficulties can, however, be overcome by the integration of various tools, including mathematical techniques such as singular value decomposition and lexical databases such as WordNet.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] The following software packages may be of interest to those wishing to experiment with vector models and implement search services based upon them.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] The **Generalized vector space model** is a generalization of the VSM used in information retrieval.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Wong *et al.* presented an analysis of the problems that the pairwise orthogonality assumption of the VSM creates.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] From here they extended the VSM to the generalized vector space model (GVSM).
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Recently Tsatsaronis focused on the first approach.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] They measure semantic relatedness (*SR*) using a thesaurus (*O*) like WordNet.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] It considers the path length, captured by compactness (*SCM*), and the path depth, captured by semantic path elaboration (*SPE*).
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Building also on the first approach, Waitelonis et al. have computed semantic relatedness from Linked Open Data resources including DBpedia as well as the YAGO taxonomy.
[src:pinecone/vector-space-model] Thereby they exploits taxonomic relationships among semantic entities in documents and queries after named entity linking.
